Cubical type theory is a constructive approach to homotopy type theory that is meant to give a computation character to HoTT. Roughly speaking, cubical type theory extends Martin-Lof type theory with a pretype, \mathbb {I}, that is interpreted as the abstract interval. The reason for extending type theory with this structure is to construct a type theory with the semantic properties of HoTT without sacrificing all the syntactic properties that imbue dependent type theory with computational character.

A cofibration logic is a first-order intuitonstic logic used in the definition of cubical type theories. Like any first-order logic, a cofibration logic is defined by a description of terms and formulas.

The terms of a cofibration logic are a specification of the structure of \mathbb {I}, the interval. The simplest interval term structure contains the endpoints 0 and 1 and arbitrary variables x_i. The most complex interval term structure contains the above and joins, meets, and complements (DeMorgan Algebra). In cubical type thoeries, the specified structure of \mathbb {I} is used to reason about the dimensions of the n-cube. Varying term definitions lead to varying levels of complexity of the path structure in a cubical type theory.

The formulas of a cofibration logic are a fragment of intuitionistic first-order equational logic over interval terms. The formulas of a cofibration logic are called cofibrations. Cofibrations are used in cubical type theory to reason about portions of paths.
Partial elements are elements of a type that are defined on the extent of a cofibration formula. Partial elements are used in cubical type theory to describe partially specified n-dimensional cubes.
I use the notation [\alpha ] \rightarrow A for the type of partial elements of A defined on \alpha . Partial elements internalize the structure of the judgement \alpha \vdash a : A.

A boundary type is a type that describes the witness of a partial element being ``extensible''. Given a partial element u : [\alpha ] \to A, the boundary type A[\alpha \to u] is the type of elements a : A that ``extend'' u. A term a : A[\alpha \to u] is a proof that a : A and u : A agree on \alpha . Any term u : A is a term of A[\alpha \to u] because u is equivalent with itself. Thus, the boundary type internalizes two judgments: \Gamma \vdash a : A and \Gamma , \alpha \vdash a \equiv u : A. Boundary types can be thought of as a \Sigma -type: \Sigma (a : A) ([\phi ] \to A \equiv u).
